en 1719 and 1726: three sons of Capt. John Hart (X00033) married three daughters of Hon. John Hooker (H00030). Nathaniel Hart married I00028's wife's sister Sarah Hooker (H00101, b.~1701); she had married Matthew Hart in 1726."}],"gender":"male","tags":[],"number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"marriage","header":"Three Hart brothers each married a Hooker sister","body":"He was one of three sons of Capt. John Hart who each married a daughter of John Hooker Esq. of Farmington — Nathaniel married Abigail, Samuel married Mary, and Matthew married Sarah, between 1719 and 1725, binding two of Farmington's founding families."}],"bio":{"display_name":"Nathaniel Hart","first_name":"Nathaniel","last_name":"Hart","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"nathaniel-hart-1695"},"H00099":{"id":"H00099","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_thomas":4,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1698,"month":6,"day":14,"city":"Farmington","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1761,"month":1,"day":1,"city":"Kensington","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States","cause":"Year only; month/day approximate per project convention. Source: 'died 1761 aged 63.'"},"parents":{"father_id":"H00030","mother_id":"I00031"},"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"I00028","children_ids":["H00268","H00269","H00270","H00271","H00272","H00273","H00274","H00275","H00276"],"marriage_number":1,"date_year":1719,"date_month":12,"date_day":3,"location_country":"United States"}],"sources":[{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909","page":"Entry 99"}],"gender":"female","tags":[],"number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"marriage","header":"She and her sisters all married Hart brothers","body":"She was one of three daughters of John Hooker Esq. of Farmington who each married a son of Capt. John Hart — Abigail to Nathaniel, Mary to Samuel, and Sarah to Matthew — between 1719 and 1725, uniting the two most prominent families of Farmington's founding generation."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Three sons served the Revolution differently","body":"Her eldest son Selah rose to General and was captured by the British in 1776; Noadiah served as Lieutenant; and Asahel, Yale-educated and ordained as a minister, died in 1775 at age 33 before the war's outcome was known. Three brothers from one Hooker-Hart household, three paths through the Revolution."}],"cross_connections":[{"type":"family_connection","related_id":"I00029","display_label":"Brother-in-law via Hart-Hooker triple marriage, 1719-1726","link_text":"Lieut. Samuel Hart","notes":"One of the three Hart-Hooker marriages between 1719 and 1726: three daughters of Hon. John Hooker (H00030) married three sons of Capt. John Hart (X00033). Lieut. Samuel Hart married Abigail Hooker's sister Mary Hooker (H00100) in 1723; Abigail Hooker married I00028 in 1719."},{"type":"family_connection","related_id":"I00030","display_label":"Brother-in-law via Hart-Hooker triple marriage, 1719-1726","link_text":"Matthew Hart","notes":"One of the three Hart-Hooker marriages between 1719 and 1726: three daughters of Hon. John Hooker (H00030) married three sons of Capt. John Hart (X00033). Matthew Hart married Abigail Hooker's sister Sarah Hooker (H00101) in 1726; Abigail Hooker married I00028 in 1719."},{"type":"in_law","related_id":"X00033","display_label":"was her father-in-law; Hartford founding Hart family"}],"bio":{"display_name":"Abigail Hooker Hart","first_name":"Abigail","last_name":"Hart","married_names":["H